"Abstract The Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) added a safe harbor provision shielding an Internet service provider (ISP) from liability for copyright infringement under certain circumstances. The effectiveness of the safe harbor defence depends on what the ISP does upon receipt of notification of copyright infringing activity from a copyright owner. In a recent Court of Appeals decision (ALS Scan Inc. v RemarQ Communities Inc. (Case No. 00-1351, United States Court of Appeals, 4th Circuit, 6 February 2001)), one ISP learned that a failure to respond properly and expeditiously to even an imperfect DMCA notification is at the ISP’s peril. Alan Wernick reports on the decision and its implications."
